00343}},{"text":"Presented a generalized version of the L2HMC algorithm—consisting of a stack of leapfrog layers—that improves the existing approaches' flexibility while remaining statistically exact.","targetRectangle":{"y":840.58062744140625,"x":2455.358154296875,"width":722.712890625,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"Shown that our trained model successfully mixes between modes of a two-dimensional  Gaussian Mixture Model while HMC remains stuck in a local mode.","targetRectangle":{"y":918.58062744140625,"x":2455.358154296875,"width":710.3701171875,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"Looked at applying the described approach to a two-dimensional U(1) lattice gauge theory.","targetRectangle":{"y":996.58062744140625,"x":2455.358154296875,"width":683.6328125,"height":51.2802734375}},{"text":"Saw that for this lattice gauge model, our trained sampler is capable of significantly outperforming traditional HMC across a range of coupling constants.","targetRectangle":{"y":1048.5806274414062,"x":2455.358154296875,"width":692.1513671875,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2266.0566482543945,"x":2604.5972097521626,"width":149.87459485060299,"height":30.086634404904544}},{"text":"Figure (h.) The real-valued topological charge ￼ at intermediate leapfrog layers.","targetRectangle":{"y":1903.52880859375,"x":2012.2420654296875,"width":376.47536096305475,"height":51.390405334044772}},{"text":"sinQf_1746.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1367.939697265625,"x":1995.88232421875,"width":392.16552734375,"height":535.04620361328125}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2135.1432657687465,"x":376.60771143436432,"width":29.033346778476016,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":545.8553466796875,"x":930.44903588294983,"width":12.707874051155954,"height":29.577245919845382}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1878.7611675754517,"x":2829.6594312834795,"width":227.65140910159289,"height":31.51331821156441}},{"text":" ￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2026.6252899169922,"x":903.3180336746758,"width":203.28107361134187,"height":37.153549632491377}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2329.4068872861772,"x":78.221969246864319,"width":263.12734271617649,"height":61.933883161797894}},{"text":"Figure (b.) Illustration of contours from the true target distribution vs samples obtained from both the trained model and generic HMC. We can see that HMC fails to mix between the two modes of the distribution whereas the trained model efficiently jumps between them.","targetRectangle":{"y":1162.07373046875,"x":850.23681640625,"width":749.26591796874982,"height":62.404589843750045}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2254.5066108703613,"x":2822.4050445556641,"width":327.47967933266773,"height":60.287962730744766}},{"text":"￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2343.6983032226562,"x":887.95772058526245,"width":307.91777645032471,"height":41.637059676190347}},{"text":"where ￼ are (collectively) the weights in the NN","targetRectangle":{"y":545.8553466796875,"x":864.41680932044983,"width":459.00279592615607,"height":29.577245919845382}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":496.521728515625,"x":898.49456787109375,"width":331.19139735555109,"height":35.109034570355334}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2011.7330125454368,"x":2870.672078469152,"width":107.7865025452661,"height":57.753090796863944}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":657.42391625925131,"x":2458.4813718399637,"width":98.648714114184259,"height":31.229445867449272}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1331.3552108033796,"x":78.221973061561584,"width":248.55208643549975,"height":30.029985258512397}},{"text":"Building topological samplers for lattice gauge theories","targetRectangle":{"y":128.19134521484375,"x":48.959396362304688,"width":1143.6431054687503,"height":47.585410156249992}},{"text":" Let ￼, with ￼      denote the link variables, where ￼ is a link at the site ￼ oriented in direction ￼.","targetRectangle":{"y":1843.8978805541992,"x":857.68763595819473,"width":529.18650584865054,"height":101.68750752422307}},{"text":"Abstract","targetRectangle":{"y":330.29306030273438,"x":374.63789367675781,"width":113.5859375,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"Wilson action ￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2043.4935302734375,"x":1168.08630412817,"width":105.6689453125,"height":47.129708531638244}},{"text":"autocorr_vs_beta_1917.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":557.3419189453125,"x":1633.9029541015625,"width":748.2801513671875,"height":252.95046997070312}},{"text":"Conclusion","targetRectangle":{"y":792.95996093750068,"x":2729.2893066406255,"width":152.44140625,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1926.52880859375,"x":2078.9510498046875,"width":29.619892213054754,"height":28.390405334044772}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":810.99200151449259,"x":2220.0261900288351,"width":11.280260660046679,"height":25.115987670755885}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1733.8964996337891,"x":489.14802169799805,"width":22.035508686581238,"height":18.142529018756704}},{"text":"pasted-image.png","targetRectangle":{"y":1222.378662109375,"x":850.23681640625,"width":746,"height":531.91227606798202}},{"text":"Training Costs","targetRectangle":{"y":498.91481781005854,"x":2710.9002654338433,"width":194.46875,"height":31.083984375000057}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1238.4100341796875,"x":115.55530548095703,"width":239.99375455645566,"height":31.229445867449385}},{"text":"hwf_1803.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1367.939697265625,"x":1640.0478515625,"width":376.3333740234375,"height":536.7542724609375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1843.8978805541992,"x":900.49525314569473,"width":231.7811908564729,"height":35.109034570355334}},{"text":"Our models were trained using Horovod on the ThetaGPU supercomputer at the Argonne Leadership Computing Facility (ALCF). A typical training run on 1 node (￼NVIDIA A100 GPUs) using a batch size ￼, hidden layer shapes ￼ for each of the ￼ leapfrog layers, on a ￼ lattice for ￼ training steps takes roughly ￼ hours to complete.","targetRectangle":{"y":544.42791206550862,"x":2458.4813718399637,"width":715.33756943690605,"height":174.72345215806342}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":402.0634765625,"x":1958.1680908203125,"width":35.431728242512008,"height":36.864618010476363}},{"text":"1 foremans@anl.gov 2 xjin@anl.gov 3 osborn@alcf.anl.gov","targetRectangle":{"y":2420.94482421875,"x":55.020828247070312,"width":464.06250059668673,"height":20.411132926179562}},{"text":"We can write a complete leapfrog update as: (compare with HMC (i.)","targetRectangle":{"y":1596.599365234375,"x":82.721968889236223,"width":667.197265625,"height":25.2802734375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2229.7780744160445,"x":354.37694787315934,"width":26.710782738234855,"height":31.43761891980057}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2343.6983032226562,"x":887.95772058526245,"width":307.91777645032471,"height":41.637059676190347}},{"text":"Method","targetRectangle":{"y":1093.69287109375,"x":380.69377136230469,"width":99.53125,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2195.5408325195312,"x":1402.0424194335938,"width":188.34910639456439,"height":46.770142120381934}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1943.2272571235806,"x":2571.8902012163067,"width":199.98942310281745,"height":34.214770049692333}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2135.1432657687465,"x":477.88658610419554,"width":27.647300489193924,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":596.42791206550862,"x":2754.4393796524637,"width":42.232859959112375,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"pasted-image.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":867.99078369140625,"x":1637.3839111328125,"width":742.944091796875,"height":203.55917358398438}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1700.2257232666016,"x":376.33309919282328,"width":11.232185309579449,"height":28.262290598076106}},{"text":"￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2296.560791015625,"x":865.29247856140137,"width":353.24826150747185,"height":41.741570356715783}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1850.9388427734375,"x":117.15413757324218,"width":27.533722426507538,"height":29.182710023683967}},{"text":"where:￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2172.5408325195312,"x":1402.0424194335938,"width":188.34910639456439,"height":69.770142120381934}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2303.0599539053974,"x":2602.5845144396626,"width":96.245044085519112,"height":24.364043619031236}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":657.42391625925131,"x":2952.393794336157,"width":78.349951628212693,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2096.3924126661909,"x":2645.3352812225403,"width":250.79182334258167,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2214.4732642129202,"x":1644.390625,"width":54.465634765625055,"height":27.299986598647592}},{"text":"Figure (c.) Summary of training algorithm.","targetRectangle":{"y":1754.284912109375,"x":850.23681640625,"width":412.005859375,"height":25.2802734375}},{"text":"leapfrog step","targetRectangle":{"y":2371.506103515625,"x":2072.870361328125,"width":115.634765625,"height":22.345703125}},{"text":"bit.ly\/l2hmc-qcd","targetRectangle":{"y":226.73585510253906,"x":2926.6318359375,"width":249.25037109374989,"height":51}},{"text":"Figure (g.) The adjusted energy ￼ at intermediate leapfrog layers.","targetRectangle":{"y":1903.52880859375,"x":1640.5313720703125,"width":342.78288368866833,"height":73.614996455540222}},{"text":"We generalize the Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC) algorithm with a stack of trainable neural network (NN) layers and evaluate its ability to sample from different topologies in a two-dimensional lattice gauge theory. We demonstrate that our model is able to successfully mix between modes of different topologies, significantly reducing the computational cost required to generate independent gauge field configurations.","targetRectangle":{"y":375.83786010742188,"x":83.373512148857117,"width":721.1337890625,"height":171.16816767887212}},{"text":"In order to keep our model reversible, we split the ￼ update into two sub-updates using a binary mask,  ￼ ￼￼ that updates half of the components of ￼ sequentially.","targetRectangle":{"y":2104.645263671875,"x":78.221969246864319,"width":703.98604519567755,"height":90.774279728113925}},{"text":"We've introduced the shorthand notation for the networks' inputs: ￼, ￼￼￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2196.1392699624889,"x":78.221969246864319,"width":637.8173828125,"height":76.049888664317223}},{"text":"We must now explicitly keep track of the Jacobian factor of the update ￼, these are easily computed to be                 ￼, ￼.","targetRectangle":{"y":2272.9088851893061,"x":78.221969246864319,"width":686.8447265625,"height":118.4318852586689}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1915.5554028199097,"x":1152.5862651199939,"width":14.020361784462693,"height":30.029985258512397}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1540.4068603515625,"x":108.24252319335938,"width":666.07648127879543,"height":41.921474773064574}},{"text":"Picture 22","targetRectangle":{"y":2438.54052734375,"x":2483.612548828125,"width":172.30680847167969,"height":68.176986694335938}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1071.3717041015625,"x":2188.6915283203125,"width":29.27580452321854,"height":28.390405334044772}},{"text":"Figure (k.) Illustration of the average plaquette vs leapfrog step for different values of ￼. Note that at ￼, the energy is shifted down past the expected value at ￼.","targetRectangle":{"y":1997.564697265625,"x":1644.390625,"width":191.240234375,"height":244.20855354594278}},{"text":"network_aligned1.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1815.0908203125,"x":51.959396362304688,"width":741.353759765625,"height":300.31637573242188}},{"text":"￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2210.7103881835938,"x":874.22823861543475,"width":246.60495083919886,"height":41.993388974635309}},{"text":"Figure (f.) Illustration of the integer valued topological charge ￼ vs MC step for both HMC (black) and the trained model (blue).","targetRectangle":{"y":1071.3717041015625,"x":1639.5313720703125,"width":718.46525764821854,"height":51.390405334044772}},{"text":"Picture 24","targetRectangle":{"y":2454.559326171875,"x":2331.97119140625,"width":141.81584167480469,"height":36.139442443847656}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1395.0866973652351,"x":258.00322306156158,"width":28.095635129089317,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1704.1631943881512,"x":488.91044998168945,"width":22.035508686581238,"height":18.142529018756704}},{"text":"Figure (a.) Illustration of the ￼ leapfrog layer.","targetRectangle":{"y":1824.9388427734375,"x":57.221969604492188,"width":228.89022633275749,"height":55.182710023683967}},{"text":"Motivation","targetRectangle":{"y":571.64532470703125,"x":361.43769836425781,"width":139.986328125,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods are pervasive throughout science and are used in applications ranging from epidemiological modeling to election forecasting.","targetRectangle":{"y":614.69677734375,"x":75.221969485282898,"width":696.9423828125,"height":85.584083839436062}},{"text":"Recent developments in ML, together with ever-more-capable hardware has led to a resurgence in developing faster, more efficient simulation techniques.","targetRectangle":{"y":700.28086118318606,"x":75.221969485282898,"width":705.5791015625,"height":85.584083839436062}},{"text":"In particular, the development of invertible NN architectures has opened the flood-gates for new approaches that are capable of outperforming traditional techniques on particularly challenging distributions.","targetRectangle":{"y":785.86494502262212,"x":75.221969485282898,"width":704.3974609375,"height":85.584083839436062}},{"text":"Simulations in lattice gauge theory \/ lattice QCD are currently limited by our ability to generate independent configurations, making it a prime target for testing novel approaches.","targetRectangle":{"y":871.44902886205819,"x":75.221969485282898,"width":730.103515625,"height":85.584083839436062}},{"text":"Here, we propose a generalized version of the L2HMC [2] and demonstrate its ability to significantly reduce the computational effort required to generate configurations for a two-dimensional ￼ lattice gauge theory.","targetRectangle":{"y":957.03311270149425,"x":75.221969485282898,"width":682.56622371495325,"height":118.63853826486525}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1926.52880859375,"x":1640.5313720703125,"width":121.54264931366811,"height":27.614996455540222}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2266.0566482543945,"x":2562.9221038818355,"width":9.6829183703271156,"height":24.364043619031236}},{"text":"Figure (e.) Estimate of the integrated autocorrelation time ￼ vs ￼, scaled by ￼ to account for simulation cost.","targetRectangle":{"y":810.2923583984375,"x":1637.3839111328125,"width":745.11869191158348,"height":52.832225972398419}},{"text":"Method (contd.)","targetRectangle":{"y":330.29306030273438,"x":1117.4276123046875,"width":209.9453125,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2104.645263671875,"x":566.13212549686432,"width":11.834678008177548,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1878.7611675754517,"x":2665.5932486389115,"width":40.541768582067562,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2298.9088851893061,"x":78.221969246864319,"width":68.434410594334111,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"1. Half-step ￼:","targetRectangle":{"y":1669.951847076416,"x":162.71540451049805,"width":147.43430276528898,"height":26.625914857378348}},{"text":"pasted-image.png","targetRectangle":{"y":1843.8978805541