":{"y":1427.2440428475352,"x":288.54326212406158,"width":83.957218348422884,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1910.9942123495161,"x":2611.8623610445675,"width":81.951295086156733,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"Next Steps","targetRectangle":{"y":330.29306030273438,"x":2732.5058593749977,"width":144.716796875,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2135.1432657687465,"x":411.75336290034033,"width":66.133223203855152,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1910.9942123495161,"x":2475.9380527788067,"width":100.46434732826128,"height":31.51331821156441}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2329.4068872861772,"x":353.5739213380408,"width":241.66726547197425,"height":61.933883161797894}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":375.83786010742188,"x":1293.1254879236221,"width":74.274747188960191,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1669.951847076416,"x":276.98165451049806,"width":26.454616419582806,"height":26.625916019146644}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1843.8978805541992,"x":1189.7364049396676,"width":160.46390874217764,"height":35.109034570355334}},{"text":"iso_gmm_chains2.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":590.3751220703125,"x":850.23681640625,"width":745.47637939453125,"height":559.1072998046875}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2303.0599539053974,"x":2560.9094085693355,"width":9.6829183703271156,"height":24.364043619031236}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2096.3924126661909,"x":2528.2163733297252,"width":104.89429851781551,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2117.5189807392726,"x":1753.345703125,"width":54.465634765625055,"height":27.299986598647592}},{"text":"qr_ecp_poster.png","targetRectangle":{"y":2442.129150390625,"x":2247.19970703125,"width":61,"height":61}},{"text":"Hamiltonian Monte Carlo (HMC)","targetRectangle":{"y":1775.24267578125,"x":2596.8918762207031,"width":419.986328125,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"For target distributions in Euclidean space, ￼, we define a loss function that encourages our sampler to move large distances in the phase space.","targetRectangle":{"y":375.83786010742188,"x":871.23681604862213,"width":672.26009875146019,"height":81.778275534371346}},{"text":"To do this, we can maximize the expected squared jump distance (ESJD): ","targetRectangle":{"y":458.33586220429322,"x":871.23681604862213,"width":723.89453125,"height":25.2802734375}},{"text":"￼","targetRectangle":{"y":1540.4068603515625,"x":108.24252319335938,"width":666.07648127879543,"height":41.921474773064574}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":657.42391625925131,"x":2768.6974687666475,"width":82.214880257009554,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2302.9384891388468,"x":865.29247856140137,"width":353.24826150747185,"height":35.363872233494021}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2472.6284507600039,"x":55.334396362304688,"width":173.30237017846713,"height":23.53399025175986}},{"text":"In order to understand the mechanism driving this improved behavior, we looked at how different physical quantities evolve during a single trajectory in the trained model as shown in Figures (g.), (h.).","targetRectangle":{"y":1131.9825439453125,"x":1653.8839111328125,"width":728.4599609375,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"We see that our sampler artificially increased the energy of the physical system during the first half of the trajectory, before returning back to its original physical value.","targetRectangle":{"y":1209.9825439453125,"x":1653.8839111328125,"width":700.2724609375,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"We believe that this ability to vary the energy during the trajectory helps the sampler to overcome energy barriers between topological sectors whereas HMC remains stuck.","targetRectangle":{"y":1287.9825439453125,"x":1653.8839111328125,"width":701.5185546875,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":810.99200151449259,"x":2324.3755913138825,"width":32.557480480514187,"height":26.119172907321285}},{"text":"Going forward we plan to continue development of this approach towards more complex theories in higher space-time dimensions (e.g. 2D, 4D SU(3)).","targetRectangle":{"y":376.0634765625,"x":2451.3642578125,"width":717.8681640625,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"discrete, hard to work with","targetRectangle":{"y":2163.0184936523438,"x":1180.6387684326171,"width":108.22615234375007,"height":39.441230468749836}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1764.9735717773438,"x":277.28528625488286,"width":26.454615265288965,"height":26.625914857378348}},{"text":"4. Half-step ￼:","targetRectangle":{"y":1764.9735717773438,"x":164.37934875488281,"width":145.99406839028899,"height":26.625914857378348}},{"text":" Target distribution: Introduce annealing factor ￼, with ￼","targetRectangle":{"y":1957.2407836914062,"x":857.68763595819473,"width":500.23054097056547,"height":62.21398542101133}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1733.8964996337891,"x":649.53054809570312,"width":22.875512299710749,"height":18.1425301001359}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2042.258186413572,"x":1291.0057067871094,"width":299.38593490634685,"height":23.986609762902162}},{"text":"3. Full-step (2nd half of ￼):","targetRectangle":{"y":1731.5851821899414,"x":162.80608463287354,"width":238.08002929136734,"height":27.612582768235143}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1362.104922624392,"x":377.81084024906158,"width":351.66071773067495,"height":32.262048178343093}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":495.44839477539062,"x":1280.1736450195312,"width":200.18450178559783,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":517.64782113547631,"x":1860.2745361328125,"width":133.18159042786215,"height":30.029985258512397}},{"text":"Deep Learning Hamiltonian Monte Carlo ","targetRectangle":{"y":25.301462173461914,"x":45.209396362304688,"width":1776.8250000000005,"height":102.98500000000001}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1878.7611675754517,"x":2604.8042637163067,"width":44.901289610105323,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2213.4334194525513,"x":874.22823861543475,"width":246.60495083919886,"height":39.270357705677725}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2229.7780744160445,"x":381.08773061139425,"width":98.799677470237498,"height":34.214770049692106}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1238.4100341796875,"x":427.69359128741269,"width":38.927422313658326,"height":31.229445867449385}},{"text":"Argonne National Laboratory","targetRectangle":{"y":249.19984436035156,"x":52.334396362304688,"width":460.30078125,"height":40.822265625}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1879.7266416870543,"x":1173.5050187706947,"width":51.931974235752477,"height":35.109034570355334}},{"text":"HMC (j.)","targetRectangle":{"y":2349.1482124328613,"x":1489.6619338989258,"width":81.8662109375,"height":25.2802734375}},{"text":"  (i.) Leapfrog update","targetRectangle":{"y":2217.7183964252472,"x":2442.9045257568359,"width":185.673828125,"height":22.345703125}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1989.3981291737066,"x":907.22083920240402,"width":85.20908925639219,"height":30.056639938710987}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1978.1617537357729,"x":2475.9380527788067,"width":447.96182780982372,"height":32.851532247163959}},{"text":"Results","targetRectangle":{"y":330.29306030273438,"x":1960.1626281738281,"width":101.14453125,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"￼","targetRectangle":{"y":2161.5184936523438,"x":875.48977690696165,"width":244.08187425614506,"height":41.993388974635309}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2074.3890762329102,"x":872.53086558603616,"width":271.562275022996,"height":39.173479461874194}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2165.6412678656179,"x":228.64482080936432,"width":11.834678008177576,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1670.2468070983887,"x":444.98661804199219,"width":126.97776138225436,"height":25.392467204579361}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":626.92591416237997,"x":2503.7167234024637,"width":108.57932060455596,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1957.2407836914062,"x":1330.4405656456947,"width":15.253001908065471,"height":31.437618919800343}},{"text":"We propose a generalized version of the L2HMC algorithm [2] that introduces distinct neural networks for each leapfrog step called leapfrog layers, shown in (a).","targetRectangle":{"y":1134.4100341796875,"x":78.221973061561584,"width":719.017578125,"height":77.2802734375}},{"text":"Denote the leapfrog step \/ layer by a discrete index ￼ where ￼ is the total number of leapfrogs.","targetRectangle":{"y":1212.4100341796875,"x":108.76005935668945,"width":672.14513393188156,"height":57.229445867449385}},{"text":"Introduce ￼ (direction—forward\/backward) and denote the complete state ￼, then the target distribution is given by ￼.","targetRectangle":{"y":1270.3592066096369,"x":78.221973061561584,"width":709.87592636536215,"height":91.025989452255089}},{"text":"Each leapfrog step transforms ￼ by passing it through ￼ leapfrog layer (note the direction, ￼ is persistent).","targetRectangle":{"y":1362.104922624392,"x":78.221973061561584,"width":699.45743823823534,"height":64.419393660643436}},{"text":"Consider the forward ￼ direction1 and introduce the notation:","targetRectangle":{"y":1427.2440428475354,"x":78.221973061561584,"width":658.34556494568415,"height":29.778275534371232}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1270.3592066096369,"x":176.06181681156158,"width":153.4628404278622,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"where ￼ is given in  ","targetRectangle":{"y":2315.6127319335933,"x":1405.4174194335938,"width":172.40744263222814,"height":55.77827553437146}},{"text":"1To obtain the expression for the reverse direction, we can invert each of the ￼ functions and perform the updates in the opposite order","targetRectangle":{"y":2449.095703125,"x":55.334396362304688,"width":678.89973980432842,"height":47.066737886763804}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2336.1961503404777,"x":2562.9221038818355,"width":9.6829183703271156,"height":24.364043619031236}},{"text":"References","targetRectangle":{"y":1175.8154296874995,"x":2732.5207621718309,"width":150.978515625,"height":31.083984375}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":689.3730886892007,"x":2595.4442624649637,"width":26.654680198598271,"height":29.778275534371346}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2126.8904147630619,"x":2854.3775059038067,"width":16.842796254381028,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":2089.564697265625,"x":1807.45703125,"width":12.261152891355096,"height":27.299986598647592}},{"text":"In order to measure the computational cost of our approach we use the integrated autocorrelation time ￼, which can be roughly interpreted as the number of trajectories (on average) before an independent sample is drawn.","targetRectangle":{"y":376.0634765625,"x":1654.8839111328125,"width":711.755859375,"height":114.86461801047636}},{"text":"We can see in Figure (e.) that the trained model consistently outperforms generic HMC across ￼.","targetRectangle":{"y":491.64782113547636,"x":1654.8839111328125,"width":721.0263671875,"height":56.02998525851234}},{"text":"  (a.) Generalized leapfrog update","targetRectangle":{"y":1634.1740131378174,"x":149.22758483886719,"width":378.73828125,"height":37}},{"text":"equation.pdf","targetRectangle":{"y":1915.5554028199097,"x":935.02845627069473,"width":13.327340099299022,"height":29.77827553437146}},{"text":" Loss function: We maximize the expected squared charge difference","targetRectangle":{"y":2266.10198